item.title: Nearly 500 people dead from Wuhan virus
China says Xi Jinping is directing its Wuhan coronavirus response, but he's nowhere to be seen
item.description: Since he first intervened in the Wuhan coronavirus crisis in late January, ordering "all-out efforts" to contain its spread, Chinese President Xi Jinping has been personally directing the country's response.

item.title: This doctor tried to save lives, but was silenced. Now he has coronavirus
First of Wuhan's two new hospitals for coronavirus patients completed
item.description: The first of Wuhan's two new medical facilities dedicated to coronavirus patients has been completed, after more than 1,000 workers and 100 machines worked non-stop for days.

Tapper on Biden: This is a bad sign for his campaign
item.description: With 62% of the precincts reporting, CNN's Jake Tapper discusses how Joe Biden's standing in the Iowa Democratic caucuses will make it difficult for his presidential campaign to pick up momentum moving forward.

US military deploys new type of nuclear weapon seen as key to countering Russia
item.description: The US military deployed a new submarine-launched low-yield nuclear weapon, something the Pentagon sees as critical to countering the threat posed by Russia's arsenal of smaller tactical nukes.

item.title: An impeachment trial with no witnesses or evidence is very American
item.description: The impeachment trial of President Donald Trump is a relative rarity in American political history, and yet aspects of it have the haunting familiarity of a sham trial in the Jim Crow South, where black people were routinely criminalized and murdered in the name of "justice." Yes, there are certainly obvious differences between this political trial and the ones that many black Americans have faced, but the common thread remains: going through a trial that has already been decided before it even began.

item.description: Shannen Doherty is facing a major health battle.

item.title: Man causes Google Maps chaos with a handcart and 99 phones
item.description: An artist in Berlin has tricked Google Maps into creating traffic jam alerts by pulling 99 phones -- with their location services on -- slowly around the German capital in a handcart.

item.description: The world's most powerful passport just got a makeover.

item.title: School meeting about racism ends with parent's racist remark
item.description: A community meeting, meant to promote diversity at Saline Area Schools in Michigan, ended in tension after a parent yelled out racist comments.

item.title: The mission to drill through the Earth's crust
item.description: Last month, floating in the ocean south of New Zealand, a team of scientists were investigating the end of the dinosaurs and trying to predict the future.

item.title: Tesla's stock is out of this world
item.description: Tesla's stock soared on Tuesday, continuing a remarkable rally in which the stock has soared for days, weeks and months.

item.title: Closed Japanese McDonald's gets tongue-in-cheek sendoff from rival Burger King
item.description: As a McDonald's in Tokyo's Akihabara neighborhood closed down after 22 years in business and posted a thank-you poster outside its store, its arch competitor Burger King responded with a seemingly compassionate adieu.

item.title: 'It's urban, but it's beautiful': NYC through the eyes of its favorite photographer
item.description: For photographer Landon Nordeman, finding beauty in the everyday is a full-time job. So, it's no surprise that his hometown of New York provides an endless source of creative and personal inspiration.

item.title: A kayaker vanished last month in the Florida Everglades. Days later, his phone washed ashore with clues
item.description: A Virginia kayaker who vanished during a solo trip in the Florida Everglades has been found after his cell phone washed ashore and authorities used it to recover data on his location.

item.title: Dentist suspended after patient dies and 14 others suffer heart infections
item.description: A New Jersey oral surgeon has agreed to a five-year license suspension and nearly $300,000 in penalties after one of his patients died and 14 others suffered serious heart infections, according to Monday's press release from the NJ Division of Consumer Affairs.

item.title: World's oldest wooden structure unearths new Neolithic skills
item.description: Archaeologists have uncovered the oldest wooden structure ever found. They believe the water well was built around 5256 B.C. by farmers.

item.title: Woman finds long-lost dog after seeing picture on beer can
item.description: It's been three years since a beloved family dog, Hazel, went missing in Iowa. Now she is set to be reunited with her family after being featured on a beer can in Florida.

item.title: Is Venice at war with itself?
item.description: In summer 2019, it looked for a moment that one of the most controversial issues in 21st century travel might be over.

item.title: 'Rubik Mona Lisa' could sell for $166,000
item.description: An artist's interpretation of Leonardo da Vinci's "Mona Lisa" -- fashioned out of hundreds of Rubik's cubes -- is expected to go under the hammer at a Paris auction later this month.

item.title: Video game arcade massacre leaves nine dead
item.description: At least nine people -- four of them minors -- have been killed and two others wounded in a shooting at a video arcade in Mexico.

item.title: With travelers unable to visit, China's museums are moving exhibitions online
item.description: Chinese travelers can't visit their country's museums right now. So the museums are bringing the exhibits to them -- virtually.

item.title: Weeks after a deadly earthquake, Puerto Rico is rattled again
item.description: A magnitude 5 earthquake on Tuesday struck Puerto Rico, where people are still on edge from a series of quakes after last month's deadly 6.4 temblor.

item.title: Asteroid that killed the dinos and wiped out most life helped repopulate Earth
item.description: The asteroid that wiped out the dinosaurs some 66 million years ago almost took all of life on Earth along with it.

item.title: Kenya's longest serving president dies at 95
item.description: Former Kenyan President Daniel Arap Moi, who ruled the country for 24 years has died, President Uhuru Kenyatta announced Tuesday. Moi was 95.

item.title: Is Johnson borrowing from Trump's media playbook?
item.description: An attempt to exclude select UK political reporters from an official briefing has led some journalists to accuse the British government of resorting to tactics used by President Donald Trump to punish the media for critical coverage.

item.title: Sand dunes can communicate, or at least give their neighbor a shove
item.description: Sand dunes are inanimate objects, so they don't think or feel, but they can communicate with their neighbors and let them know they need space, according to research published by scientists at Cambridge University.

item.title: When Pluto's frozen heart beats, it creates wind
item.description: During its flyby of Pluto in 2015, NASA's New Horizons mission captured a now iconic image of a heart-shaped feature on the dwarf planet. And new research about Pluto's "frozen heart" has revealed that its "heartbeat" actually controls wind, which could sculpt the landscape on its surface.

item.description: Framed by abundant woodland, surrounded by icy water and bathed in the glowing winter sun, this new hotel in Swedish Lapland already sounds pretty special.
